DSA-002C

> A variable in Java is a name given to a memory location that stores a value which can be changed during program execution.
> 

---

### ğŸ”¹ **Why Use Variables?**

To store data like numbers, text, or results which can be reused and updated.

---

### ğŸ”¹ **Types of Variables in Java:**

| Type | Example | Use |
| --- | --- | --- |
| int | `int age = 20;` | Stores integers (whole numbers) |
| float/double | `double pi = 3.14;` | Decimal values |
| char | `char grade = 'A';` | Single character |
| String | `String name = "Bablu";` | Group of characters (text) |
| boolean | `boolean pass = true;` | true / false values |

---

### ğŸ”¹ **Syntax**

```
dataType variableName = value;

```

ğŸ“Œ Example:

```java
int a = 10;
String name = "Bablu";

```

---

### ğŸ§  **Logic in 1 Line:**

> Variable = a container to store value (number, text, etc.)
> 

---

### ğŸ’» Code

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int age = 24;
        double pi = 3.141;
        char grade = 'A';
        String name = "Bablu";
        boolean passed = true;

        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("Grade: " + grade);
        System.out.println("Passed: " + passed);
    }
}
```
